      "source": "Yes â€” **exactly right** âœ…\nYouâ€™ve stated the core idea **correctly**.\n\nLet me restate it cleanly and then explain *why*.\n\n---\n\n## âœ… Correct statement (polished)\n\n> **Since interface methods are abstract, the implementing class must provide their implementation.**\n\nThatâ€™s the rule.\n\n---\n\n## Why this is true\n\n### 1ï¸âƒ£ Interface methods have **no implementation**\n\n```java\ninterface FlightEnabled {\n    void fly();\n}\n```\n\nThis means:\n\n* No method body\n* No logic\n* Just a contract\n\nJava is saying:\n\n> â€œAnyone who claims to be `FlightEnabled` MUST define how `fly()` works.â€\n\n---\n\n### 2ï¸âƒ£ A class that `implements` an interface\n\n```java\nclass Bird implements FlightEnabled {\n```\n\nJava enforces:\n\nâœ” You **must implement**:\n\n```java\npublic void fly() { ... }\n```\n\nIf you donâ€™t â†’ âŒ compile-time error.\n\n---\n\n## What if the class does NOT implement the method?\n\n### âŒ Compile error\n\n```java\nclass Bird implements FlightEnabled {\n    // missing fly()\n}\n```\n\nError:\n\n```\nBird is not abstract and does not override abstract method fly()\n```\n\n---\n\n## Exception (important): abstract class implementing interface\n\n```java\nabstract class AbstractBird implements FlightEnabled {\n    // no fly() implementation\n}\n```\n\nThis is allowed because:\n\n* Abstract classes are allowed to leave methods unimplemented\n* Responsibility is pushed down\n\n---\n\n## When does implementation become mandatory?\n\n> **The FIRST concrete class in the inheritance chain must implement all interface methods.**\n\n---\n\n## Key difference: `extends` vs `implements`\n\n| Keyword      | Used for                         |\n| ------------ | -------------------------------- |\n| `extends`    | Inheriting a class               |\n| `implements` | Fulfilling an interface contract |\n\n---\n\n## Very important rule about visibility\n\nWhen implementing interface methods:\n\nâŒ Wrong:\n\n```java\nvoid fly() { }\n```\n\nâœ… Correct:\n\n```java\npublic void fly() { }\n```\n\nWhy?\n\n* Interface methods are **implicitly public**\n* You cannot reduce visibility\n\n---\n\n## One-line mental model (remember this)\n\n> **Interfaces define â€œwhat must be doneâ€; implementing classes define â€œhow it is done.â€**\n\n---\n\n## Interview-ready answer\n\n> â€œInterface methods are abstract by default, so any concrete class implementing the interface must provide their implementation; otherwise, the class itself must be abstract.â€\n\nIf you want next, I can:\n\n* Explain **default methods**\n* Show **why Java added default methods**\n* Show **real compile-time errors**\n* Compare **implements vs extends traps**\n\nJust say ğŸ‘\n",
